document.title: Head Start Early Learning Outcomes Framework

0D6C8D1BB7F44968BEFCD85BF36A0490.description: Identifies and follows basic safety rules with adult guidance and support, such as transportation and street safety practices.

BB039150383C4D6794F5A5DCDF901B89.description: Identifies, avoids, and alerts others to danger, such as keeping a safe distance from swings.

11D4621070DF41ACA4BAB5527100C683.description: Exhibits increasing independence in following basic personal safety practices and routines. Follows adult guidance around more complex practices.

4E16D6C095884553AA53DE0D564A3924.description: Child demonstrates knowledge of personal safety practices and routines.

20A8C967F9384DC4B1D84E33F8BEDF99.description: Moderates food consumption based on awareness of own hunger and fullness.

38AE2C3399A84992B863742E4F00442D.description: Demonstrates basic understanding that eating a variety of foods helps the body grow and be healthy.

C48A218B008A4ED4BC63D7D0E7792AF7.description: Identifies a variety of healthy and unhealthy foods.

5145F85727524C67AADDB197090AEFC8.description: Demonstrates an increasing understanding of the ways in which foods and nutrition help the body grow and be healthy. Makes healthy eating choices both independently and with support.

D9EE2FADA8064A8EBE80B096DB0AFC46.description: Child develops knowledge and skills that help promote nutritious food choices and eating habits.

39669871BF5A44A4AE3119B0B7381688.description: Demonstrates increasing ability to take responsibility for participating in personal self-care skills, such as brushing teeth or getting dressed.

2FF80706E2BF440E913F16A925F58272.description: Washes hands with soap and water. Knows to do this before eating, after using the bathroom, or after blowing nose.

7658A8830BE64B25A081941A35E4E7B4.description: Begins to take more responsibility for personal hygiene and self-care skills. Sometimes completes them without adult prompting.

70D963206B8144B4AB980FA7907B2E3F.description: Child demonstrates personal hygiene and self-care skills.

D036A16A20AF4B9B80EFF0582F8F430B.description: Uses coordinated movements to complete complex tasks, such as cutting along a line, pouring, or buttoning.

4EE209B81D9C4B408E1BDEDCF1CA39E9.description: Uses a pincer grip to hold and manipulate tools for writing, drawing, and painting.

5CA70E76137D42A6A40FFBB5BFDCAE7D.description: Easily coordinates hand and eye movements to carry out tasks, such as working on puzzles or stringing beads together.

2C9A099A5BC142D8A9AC4D119897B2C3.description: Performs tasks that require more complex hand-eye coordination, such as cutting out shapes and drawing letter-like forms, with moderate levels of precision and control.

78AFFE8834004DE5BAE9CC430ACC5BFE.description: Child demonstrates increasing control, strength, and coordination of small muscles.

68FE88B603B04EA2AC083BDB76628A67.description: Changes directions when moving with little difficulty.

83F4C922C1144A8397DD190510C42662.description: When asked, can move own body in front of, to the side, or behind something or someone else, such as getting in line with other children.

1F29BED61AC44D439BA7F7A0B97615A8.description: Moves body in relation to objects to effectively perform tasks, such as moving body in position to kick a ball.

F1F37760C47346BD8E6007AFD95F3CEE.description: Demonstrates awareness of own body and other people’s space during interactions.

450E2C9F536B4AAA90ABD6108F9ABA17.description: Shows increasing awareness of body, space, and relationship to other objects in ways that allow for more coordinated movements, actions, and interactions with others.

3F4FF1DCE77F4F5FA25F54EA1AD837C0.description: Child uses perceptual information to guide motions and interactions with objects and other people.

AEEC6EEEE8E94E429B8D6F7DC0B7708B.description: Demonstrates strength and stamina that allow for participation in a range of physical activities, such as running around playing tag.

CF67929D7DA748889FC4C664A9BDE2C5.description: Performs activities that combine and coordinate large muscle movements, including swinging on a swing, climbing a ladder, or dancing to music.

C055D2DE44DF4E79AB7A0DB7622B381A.description: Demonstrates balance in large-muscle movement, such as walking on a log without falling or balancing on one leg.

C14353BD243D4A0A94CF00177659F065.description: Balances, such as on one leg or on a beam, for longer periods of time both when standing still and when moving from one position to another. Demonstrates more coordinated movement when engaging in skills, such as jumping for height and distance, hopping, and running. Engages in more complex movements, such as riding a tricycle, with ease. Engages in physical activities of increasing levels of intensity for sustained periods of time.

908B5C9132164C27B8E9EE3CB01B6B1B.description: Child demonstrates control, strength, and coordination of large muscles.

2A23DFACBCBE4319805FF817F7698F15.description: Domain: Perceptual, Motor, and Physical Development

0A7DFC2670AE48F0ADCD51BD2A2B14BB.description: Communicates results, solutions, and conclusions through a variety of methods, such as telling an adult that plants need water to grow or putting dots on a map that show the number of children from each country.

915A56FCA1B34F35B0C17B63C5DC3944.description: With adult support, compares results to initial prediction and offers evidence as to why they do or do not work. Generates new testable questions based on results.

D6DC248EBFCB4005A7F5CC5618B3A8A3.description: Draws conclusions, constructs explanations, and verbalizes cause and effect relationships.

E7ACA46D25D241BBA742C8C27BB9471D.description: Analyzes and interprets data and summarizes results of investigation.

E09E8EC69370417EA552BBC5AED90790.description: With adult assistance, analyzes and interprets data. Draws conclusions and provides simple descriptions of results. For example, an adult suggests counting how many dolls can be supported by a bridge before it breaks and along with the children counts, “One, two, three dolls. What happened when we put on the next doll?” A child says, “The bridge broke!”

FDBF0F5B296646259CEAB9DB51ECF341.description: Child analyzes results, draws conclusions, and communicates results.

535EEED35DA34E5790AA5133F605C245.description: Uses senses and simple tools to observe, gather, and record data, such as gathering data on where children’s families are from and creating a graph that shows the number of children from different countries.

4420DEC719104C3DB22B5C09843725FE.description: Implements steps and uses materials to explore testable questions, such as “Do plants need water to grow?” by planting seeds and giving water to some but not to others.

5575E3AAFFDE4F2B99F7A84B56570FF0.description: Articulates steps to be taken and lists materials needed for an investigation or experiment.

15BD052E297F44DCAA615CA1FEF037F4.description: With adult support, engages in simple investigations and experiments, such as building a “bridge” out of classroom materials and seeing how many dolls it will hold before it collapses. Records data with teacher assistance, mostly using pictures and marks on a page.

A049C90B3DA1452F89071535C18757D4.description: Child plans and conducts investigations and experiments.

0C683FEA244B49ABB87E6BEAE885F3EE.description: Makes predictions and brainstorms solutions based on background knowledge and experiences, such as “I think that plants need water to grow.” or “I think adding yellow paint to purple will make brown.”

308377A62FF24D8F8B71FD6CA349C5B2.description: Gathers information about a question by looking at books or discussing prior knowledge and observations.

AA27248240D948D781CDACE037323FB8.description: Asks questions that can be answered through an investigation, such as “What do plants need to grow?” or “What countries do the children in our class come from?”

02B3D1FBBD7844F3878566A42B491B6E.description: Asks simple questions. Uses adults as primary resources to gather information about questions. With adult support and modeling, makes simple predictions, such as “I think that the golf ball will be heavier than the ping pong ball.”

DBA9186C0D9E4AB6BD38FAC2C780D3FB.description: Child asks a question, gathers information, and makes predictions.

3D716D57AC5E468282ABDE859E7109F0.description: Uses measurement tools, such as a ruler, balance scale, eye dropper, unit blocks, thermometer, or measuring cup, to quantify similarities and differences of observable phenomena.

68D1A622AC7E4990A621E8F55B233300.description: Categorizes by sorting observable phenomena into groups based on attributes such as appearance, weight, function, ability, texture, odor, and sound.

573CCA9C0D174E62901E201DD322AB0E.description: Sorts objects into groups based on simple attributes, such as color. With support, uses measurement tools to quantify similarities and differences of observable phenomena, such as when a child scoops sand into two containers and with adult assistance, determines which container holds more scoops.

9D10290197CE4890A77F350BA77D2F43.description: Child compares and categorizes observable phenomena.

F8D117AFE50F48A9B919B4A1866A1E9D.description: Uses scientific content words when investigating and describing observable phenomena, such as parts of a plant, animal, or object.

FCBDFA36E8B74F6B9266B516E3C4A327.description: Uses scientific practice words or signs, such as observe, describe, compare, contrast, question, predict, experiment, reflect, cooperate, or measure.

A666ACF6B499460CAA7F01F0947E8C64.description: Begins to use scientific vocabulary words with modeling and support from an adult. Sometimes repeats new words offered by adults.

6497673AD4DF4EC59B9303E2ED09DA5B.description: Represents observable phenomena with pictures, diagrams, and 3-D models.

AC37B4674CCD420F92CF3A0065FAC35F.description: Describes observable phenomena using adjectives and labels, such as lemons taste sour and play dough feels sticky.

D52B171FBCE045158B412EECBA41FCA6.description: Uses observational tools to extend the five senses, such as a magnifying glass, microscope, binoculars, or stethoscope.

E2CD650F945F47DA86F1D8EF5B65C8E2.description: Identifies the five senses (smell, touch, sight, sound, taste) and uses them to make observations.

83518B65CBA5408093C57AB6ECE4F16D.description: Uses the five senses to observe objects, materials, organisms, and events. Provides simple verbal or signed descriptions. With adult support, represents observable phenomena, such as draws a picture.

C1AB2E34D37D498A90C1DCCB371A5C2B.description: Child observes and describes observable phenomena (objects, materials, organisms, and events).

9891AA70373C4EB0BE77F8CCA058B819.description: Communicates results, solutions, and conclusions through a variety of methods, such as telling an adult that plants need water to grow or putting dots on a map that show the number of children from each country.

85C2FABB1B6247D487B4FE5ED388A01A.description: With adult support, compares results to initial prediction and offers evidence as to why they do or do not work. Generates new testable questions based on results.

984657D036FD47BDA86160161EE1F335.description: Draws conclusions, constructs explanations, and verbalizes cause and effect relationships.

85C6AADDB0FD4024AD75A3D02707649A.description: Analyzes and interprets data and summarizes results of investigation.

15E4A5C387924F9E8170369FEA948356.description: With increasing independence, analyzes and interprets data and draws conclusions. With adult support, compares results to initial prediction and generates new questions or designs. For example, after putting multiple magnets together to create one magnet that is not strong enough to lift 10 paperclips, builds another and tries again. Communicates results, solutions, and conclusions in increasingly complex ways through multiple methods.

EAA299749EE64834A51A5822414DA9C8.description: Child analyzes results, draws conclusions, and communicates results.

EF24147CF9114DB1A24452BF072601A2.description: Uses senses and simple tools to observe, gather, and record data, such as gathering data on where children’s families are from and creating a graph that shows the number of children from different countries.

604EFB82DC374D43A2D78CE4CD22F816.description: Implements steps and uses materials to explore testable questions, such as “Do plants need water to grow?” by planting seeds and giving water to some but not to others.

58EE8F3CDDF2459887385D8CA8C5B8FC.description: Articulates steps to be taken and lists materials needed for an investigation or experiment.

69F391FB460C48E9AB73116D283C245D.description: With increasing independence, engages in some parts of conducting complex investigations or experiments. Increasingly able to articulate the steps that need to be taken to conduct an investigation. Uses more complex ways to gather and record data, such as with adult support, makes a graph that shows children’s favorite snacks.

96A5F32F0CCD4B00A3E207C9AC982CE2.description: Child plans and conducts investigations and experiments.

ACA53EE913DC433B85069279C4531807.description: Makes predictions and brainstorms solutions based on background knowledge and experiences, such as “I think that plants need water to grow.” or “I think adding yellow paint to purple will make brown.”

731768522979465487F4E67E00B1D9AC.description: Gathers information about a question by looking at books or discussing prior knowledge and observations.

BCA590998AC44463938C2A990B200EC1.description: Asks questions that can be answered through an investigation, such as “What do plants need to grow?” or “What countries do the children in our class come from?”

FA0D52D0EA4949589BFD0BAB9120A8FE.description: Asks more complex questions. Uses other sources besides adults to gather information, such as books, or other experts. Uses background knowledge and experiences to make predictions.

56B3D6AE99054D62A71487A076CD9CA5.description: Child asks a question, gathers information, and makes predictions.

C350928E158A44ABBC4F7CFB94A2C42B.description: Uses measurement tools, such as a ruler, balance scale, eye dropper, unit blocks, thermometer, or measuring cup, to quantify similarities and differences of observable phenomena.

22AE5F498F6E416488609B533FF813BE.description: Categorizes by sorting observable phenomena into groups based on attributes such as appearance, weight, function, ability, texture, odor, and sound.

4DCAEC3BA0DA4661BFD94680CE836392.description: With increasing independence, sorts objects into groups based on more complex attributes, such as weight, sound, or texture. Uses measurement tools to assess the properties of and compare observable phenomena.

58BB28DD670A4903B08BC8BBB82DF3B2.description: Child compares and categorizes observable phenomena.

3F063C557F0041AA84F84ECFD752CF21.description: Uses scientific content words when investigating and describing observable phenomena, such as parts of a plant, animal, or object.

E30F7748CD604E96AC68FD78A218401B.description: Uses scientific practice words or signs, such as observe, describe, compare, contrast, question, predict, experiment, reflect, cooperate, or measure.

1358D98645A3435C8A9709CD493A65E6.description: Uses a greater number of scientific vocabulary words. Repeats new words offered by adults and may ask questions about unfamiliar words.

4DDC6C585A544C189CF830E1A1098AD1.description: Represents observable phenomena with pictures, diagrams, and 3-D models.

8505E0AF495640D9984A117C31433441.description: Describes observable phenomena using adjectives and labels, such as lemons taste sour and play dough feels sticky.

9C05996CF8D8497CAE33CBC4C5D5EA81.description: Uses observational tools to extend the five senses, such as a magnifying glass, microscope, binoculars, or stethoscope.

63A18F81AFB24A79A33C824F0A77BDF2.description: Identifies the five senses (smell, touch, sight, sound, taste) and uses them to make observations.

703B2005C2284DB4945321F6501163E3.description: Makes increasingly complex observations of objects, materials, organisms, and events. Provides greater detail in descriptions. Represents observable phenomena in more complex ways, such as pictures that include more detail.

227F3B09F6D6470281C160E06F50F469.description: Child observes and describes observable phenomena (objects, materials, organisms, and events).

2BA4FAA662A04AAC875018F8DADD32B0.description: Correctly follows directions involving their own position in space, such as “Stand up” and “Move forward.”

136C75D3031941F28CC552C8D50518D0.description: Understands and uses language related to directionality, order, and the position of objects, including up/down, and in front/behind.

BF933F33E6594FDD907C0772ED5B5AF5.description: Increasingly understands spatial vocabulary. Follows directions involving their own position in space, such as “Move to the front of the line.”

BF44C299B35A470FAE4740848227A4F8.description: Child explores the positions of objects in space.

EDCBC1DC92CF49CF8DA07A47C30D155E.description: Creates and builds shapes from components.

1F76B8610E034022877912FCCA833025.description: Analyzes, compares and sorts twoand three-dimensional shapes and objects in different sizes. Describes their similarities, differences, and other attributes, such as size and shape.

13A59D11C4CD4F5294267E444DEFE264.description: Correctly names basic shapes regardless of size and orientation.

F8005A7527764A508B296D1B823F759B.description: Names and describes shapes in terms of length of sides, number of sides, and number of angles.

5F944A6BCFF54C3493FC236E35BE4402.description: Recognizes and compares a greater number of shapes of different sizes and orientations. Begins to identify sides and angles as distinct parts of shapes.

EFCFF4E36D91427F9F2FB889E5CC688B.description: Child identifies, describes, compares, and composes shapes.

D1F6210A4F8846B2AD9496002B6E5842.description: Uses comparative language, such as shortest, heavier, or biggest.

77DB66C6DACD4250BE316148E50554A8.description: Compares or orders up to 5 objects based on their measurable attributes, such as height or weight.

343239B2FA374C47A06B99A29F394A88.description: Measures using the same unit, such as putting together snap cubes to see how tall a book is.

B75880B165354256B2FBCF762926C3F2.description: With some adult support, uses measurable attributes to make comparisons, such as identifies objects as the same/different and more/less.

0A474DE1A02D44CD83F0261089989B52.description: Child measures objects by their various attributes using standard and non-standard measurement. Uses differences in attributes to make comparisons.

5D3915A5176549CEAF852A39E8801D72.description: Identifies the core unit of sequentially repeating patterns, such as color in a sequence of alternating red and blue blocks.

0994549D0C3F4152954BD0484CD434C1.description: Duplicates simple patterns in a different location than demonstrated, such as making the same alternating color pattern with blocks at a table that was demonstrated on the rug. Extends patterns, such as making an eight block tower of the same pattern that was demonstrated with four blocks.

F1E92FCDB90A4FF58CEFA9E95B4833E7.description: Fills in missing elements of simple patterns.

2517153DA47A4627AEEF9134CBF0757E.description: Creates, identifies, extends, and duplicates simple repeating patterns in different forms, such as with objects, numbers, sounds, and movements.

E0643C12E14A418BBAB4DBA268F3BE3F.description: With adult assistance, begins to use counting on from the larger number for addition. For example, when adding a group of 3 and a group of 2, counts “One, two, three…” and then counts on “Four, five!” (keeping track with fingers). When counting back for subtraction such as taking away 3 from 5, counts, “Five, four, three…two!” (keeping track with fingers).

9DAD620895D7405D95139EBEDF4B0327.description: Begins to add and subtract very small collections of objects with adult support. For example, the teacher says, “You have 3 grapes and get 1 more. How many in all?” Child counts out 3, then counts out 1 more, then counts all 4: “1, 2, 3, 4. I have 4!”

0C09398A1662433190530D89F5A38D16.description: Solves addition problems by joining objects together and subtraction problems by separating, using manipulatives and fingers to represent objects.

9EE34413665E48F4838E77400C3EAB0D.description: Child understands addition as adding to and understands subtraction as taking away from.

BF540306EF0C42CFB102CF7593ADC791.description: Recognizes and, with support, writes some numerals up to 10.

83200BB12E104DEF9548E087F9A8E9AF.description: Associates a number of objects with a written numeral 0–5.

8681475C988943FB8AE9733F8E72C7E0.description: Understands that written numbers represent quantities of objects, and uses information symbols, such as a tally, to represent numerals. With adult support, writes some numerals up to 10.

B5AC4AA1B68140DA87DEAD14988068B3.description: Child associates a quantity with written numerals up to 5 and begins to write numbers.

F04478D03E72449880943A5076AB0092.description: Identifies and uses numbers related to order or position from first to tenth.

9F7347493B104A3A9851631432ADB64B.description: Identifies whether the number of objects in one group is more than, less than, or the same as objects in another group for up to at least five objects.

CEFD5234CEF44BD88E644F1161E9C3DD.description: Counts to determine and compare number amounts even when the larger group’s objects are smaller in size, such as buttons, compared with the smaller group’s objects that are larger in size, such as markers. Uses numbers related to order or position.

C69811E0E99F4FA2B7622E998B0CE63E.description: Understands that the last number said represents the number of objects in a set.

4C45F22E18FB4D09B4AF242972708241.description: Understands that each successive number name refers to a quantity that is one larger.

47634D3BED724264B2992B74708F3188.description: Accurately counts as many as 5 objects in a scattered configuration.

DF97B821AE374C52B8B13029A2AB3026.description: Counts and answers “How many?” questions for approximately 10 objects.

EB56B4843F3741D9AC903453C71F1004.description: When counting objects, says or signs the number names in order, pairing one number word that corresponds with one object, up to at least 10.

55A1C205A86A4BC3946AE580FC330228.description: Understands that number words refer to quantity. May point to or move objects while counting objects to 10 and beyond (one-to-one correspondence). Understands that the last number represents how many objects are in a group (cardinality).

019CF96A84D94A329E53EAE6F36F3466.description: Child understands the relationship between numbers and quantities.

B8657D7D78F84CBBBD42CB5B65191C01.description: Instantly recognizes, without counting, small quantities of up to 5 objects and says or signs the number.

348458C788B8472EA410AF6C452A4C27.description: Quickly recognizes the number of objects in a small set (referred to as “subitizing”).

134B9DF424A54FDB9D73EF82BFE4E274.description: Child recognizes the number of objects in a small set.

FFAD9A38D7054E01A8F6E3D38A0AAF53.description: Counts verbally or signs to at least 20 by ones.

426C415553FC4A17942EA4B4D6CAC567.description: Says or signs more number words in sequence.

1ADB4200C0FA4C6290FD59ED3F116E74.description: Child knows number names and the count sequence.

970E62966C19477BAAE2FE3E0125E5E8.description: Writes (draws, illustrates) for a variety of purposes and demonstrates evidence of many aspects of print conventions, such as creating a book that moves left to right.

604B2743186642BD9CA16894428AEF9C.description: Writes first name correctly or close to correctly.

F9F98EF905B5480E93C90534B66FFF9B.description: Attempts to independently write some words using invented spelling, such as K for kite.

347E2DE756A04D65A9E14756D8650AB3.description: Shows an interest in copying simple words posted in the classroom.

321CF343976548EA9340A1EF1433F269.description: Creates a variety of written products that may or may not phonetically relate to intended messages.

3F4AEA27AE7644849635B5F0B4D3C5BD.description: Progressively uses drawing, scribbling, letter-like forms, and letters to intentionally convey meaning. With support, may use invented spelling consisting of salient or beginning sounds, such as L for elevator or B for bug.

D31FAB577463402C9DE93617024B4010.description: Child writes for a variety of purposes using increasingly sophisticated marks.

7BD6E5EA15034E28A5A9548BD3E62A6F.description: Provides a summary of a story, highlighting a number of the key ideas in the story and how they relate.

7AED979EE8E34090945A6F81EEE28283.description: Answers increasingly complex inferential questions that require making predictions based on multiple pieces of information from the story; inferring characters’ feelings or intentions; or providing evaluations of judgments that are grounded in the text.

4E6DD118DB8F4E8DBFF97098D43494C4.description: Answers questions about details of a story with increasingly specific information, such as when asked “Who was Mary?” responds “She was the girl who was riding the horse and then got hurt.”

5FDACBBE82D244B9AA5278905562CCCA.description: With support, provides basic answers to specific questions about details of a story, such as who, what, when, or where. With support, can answer inferential questions about stories, such as predictions or how/why something is happening in a particular moment.

6F2DBADA61B14A2C9803ECFEE24DB183.description: Child asks and answers questions about a book that was read aloud.

486631AB7A7F40E89F184B5FC42650C3.description: Identifies characters and main events in books and stories.

D9E1D0EB73734A30B666F2322C87DAF6.description: Tells fictional or personal stories using a sequence of at least 2–3 connected events.

E22397A14E6D44688C94A0154354FC12.description: Re-tells or acts out a story that was read, putting events in the appropriate sequence, and demonstrating more sophisticated understanding of how events relate, such as cause and effect relationships.

766684909BE94860A74B8CD8715A61A9.description: Re-tells 2–3 key events from a well-known story, typically in the right temporal order and using some simple sequencing terms, such as first … and then.

D2C48CDC977E44B992BEE3B85453405A.description: Child demonstrates an understanding of narrative structure through storytelling/re-telling.

3E3C05F1CDAC40A497E5F12BA78E051C.description: Knows the sounds associated with several letters.

28F5760BB28F4604806080171F3EF212.description: Recognizes and names at least half of the letters in the alphabet, including letters in own name (first name and last name), as well as letters encountered often in the environment. Produces the sound of many recognized letters.

5780386444A1438C8811CE75C078A1B8.description: Child identifies letters of the alphabet and produces correct sounds associated with letters.

00627CDFC23F4F478113EE7CA36564C5.description: Identifies book parts and features, such as the front, back, title, and author.

53BE844BC45241DB818EE8AA50017453.description: Begins to point to single-syllable words while reading simple, memorized texts.

76A12B58D35C46CEAF929E2FEE0DCB8A.description: Understands that written words are made up of a group of individual letters.

678B2604A6534AE5942B9D1BF9D5F9FC.description: Understands that print is organized differently for different purposes, such as a note, list, or storybook.

1BB655E09DF74092B8D3D15D35116C01.description: Begins to demonstrate an understanding of the connection between speech and print. Shows a growing awareness that print is a system that has rules and conventions, such as holding a book correctly or following a book left to right.

5146F30DBBBA45A8AC98304DBB5CCCBA.description: Child demonstrates an understanding of how print is used (functions of print) and the rules that govern how print works (conventions of print).

30056E16E5074E248B61D542E12F53A6.description: Provides a word that fits with a group of words sharing an initial sound, with adult support, such as “Sock, Sara, and song all start with the /s/ sound. What else starts with the /s/ sound?”

6E7B6DFB0731421BA17D0A2B87E1E4B2.description: Produces the beginning sound in a spoken word, such as “Dog begins with /d/.”

3C08651B02A44A41A0FDA39241F31B4D.description: Provides one or more words that rhyme with a single given target, such as “What rhymes with log?”

092887632F144C4CAF120897EAC3819A.description: Demonstrates rhyme recognition, such as identifying which words rhyme from a group of three: hat, cat, log. Recognizes phonemic changes in words, such as noticing the problem with “Old McDonald had a charm.” Is able to count syllables and understand sounds in spoken words.

FF617289A61744D889D221B264AE5A46.description: Child demonstrates awareness that spoken language is composed of smaller segments of sound.
